collection1.name: P10550.035
collection1.type: Black & white - Glass original postcard negative
collection1.author: Thuillier, Louis
collection1.description:
Portrait of Chaplain (4th Class) James Patrick Gilbert MC (left), 15th Brigade, from Randwick, NSW and Captain Keith McKeddie Doig MC, 60th Battalion medical officer from Princes Hill, Victoria. Chaplain Gilbert was awarded the Military Cross in January 1917 for actions at Fromelles. Under heavy fire, Chaplain Gilbert had tended the wounded and dying unceasingly for 48 hours. On 1 January 1918 Captain Doig was also awarded the Military Cross, for his courage and devotion to duty during the Somme fighting. The two returned home to Australia.
From the Thuillier collection of glass plate negatives. Taken by Louis and Antoinette Thuillier in Vignacourt, France during the period 1916 to 1918.

collection1.name: P10550.038
collection1.type: Black & white - Glass original postcard negative
collection1.author: Thuillier, Louis
collection1.description:
Group portrait of three members of the 13th Light Trench Mortar Battery. The sergeant on the far left has a Military Medal and Bar and is possibly 2234 Sgt Charles Thompson MM. Positively identified in this photograph is 3750 Corporal (Cpl) Robert Chaffey Stuart (far right). A labourer from Naracoorte SA, he embarked with the 12th Battalion in December 1915, was transferred to the 52nd Battalion in March 1916 with the 'doubling' of the AIF, and then to the 13th Light Trench Mortar Battery in July of the same year. In January 1919 he was awarded the Meritorious Service Medal, and returned to Australia in May of the same year. See also P10550.133 and P10550.596. 
From the Thuillier collection of glass plate negatives. Taken by Louis and Antoinette Thuillier in Vignacourt, France during the period 1916 to 1918.

collection1.name: P10550.039
collection1.type: Black & white - Glass original postcard negative
collection1.author: Thuillier, Louis
collection1.description:
Portrait of Lieutenant (Lt) Herbert Crowther Foxton (left) and 2nd Lt Cecil Arthur Auchterlonie MC and bar (right), 25th Battalion. Lt (later Captain) Foxton, a watchmaker from Ireland, enlisted in Toowoomba, Queensland. He was gassed in October 1917 and later suffered serious shrapnel wounds to his face in July 1918. He was sent to hospital in England where he underwent a series of operations to reconstruct his face (see AWM photos P06131.001 - .012). Captain Foxton returned to Australia in 1921.
2nd Lt (later Lt) Auchterlonie, a clerk from Gympie, Queensland, was awarded the Military Cross for actions near Villers Brettoneux in July 1918. Later that month he was awarded a bar to his Military Cross. He was killed in action on 10 August 1918.

collection1.name: P10550.133

collection1.author: Thuillier, Louis
collection1.description:
Group portrait of four members of the 13th Australian Light Trench Mortar Battery. The two soldiers in the front row hold bottles of French wine. Identified in this photograph are 3750 Corporal (Cpl) Robert Chaffey Stuart (third from left) and 3489 Private (Pte) John Charles Bitton (fourth from left). Stuart, a labourer from Naracoorte SA, embarked with the 12th Battalion in December 1915, was transferred to the 52nd Battalion in March 1916, and then to the 13th Light Trench Mortar Battery in July of the same year. In January 1919 he was awarded the Meritorious Service Medal. Bitton, a labourer from Maylands WA, embarked with the 28th Battalion in January 1916, was transferred to the 51st Battalion in March of the same year and then to the 13th Light Trench Mortar Battery in July. In March 1919 he was Mentioned in Despatches for his service. Both men returned to Australia in May 1919. The soldiers in this photograph each posed for their own individual portraits. In these portraits they are each wearing the same helmet, suggesting it was a prop owned by the photographers. See P10550.653, P10550.236, P10550.690, P10550.596 and P10550.422. 
From the Thuillier collection of glass-plate negatives. Taken by Louis and Antoinette Thuillier in Vignacourt, France during the period 1916 to 1918.

collection1.name: P10550.173

collection1.author: Thuillier, Louis
collection1.description:
Portrait of five Australian soldiers. Identified, left, is 2904 Sergeant (Sgt) Angus Valentine Wilson, 4th Pioneer Battalion (middle row, left), a milkman from Williamstown, Victoria, and 1144 Private (later Lieutenant) Ernest Edward Cruickshank (back row, left), 18th Battalion, a clerk from Sydney, New South Wales. Sgt Angus Wilson originally embarked with the 14th Battalion and was transferred to the 4th Pioneer Battalion in March 1916. Sgt Wilson was awarded the Military Medal for courage and determination while leading a platoon on the night of 4 July, 1918. His platoon marked out a communication trench between the front line and support trenches under heavy enemy fire. (See also P10550.173) Private Ernest Cruickshank was awarded the Military Medal for his conduct on 19 May 1918. As a sergeant he took command of his company when all his officers had been wounded. His company pressed forward with their attack, capturing their sector of the objective under his leadership. 
From the Thuillier collection of glass plate negatives. Taken by Louis and Antoinette Thuillier in Vignacourt, France during the period 1916 to 1918.

Lt Bechervaise was awarded the Military Cross for conspicuous bravery and good leadership on the morning of 10 August 1918. collection1.type: Black & white - Glass original postcard negative
collection1.author: Thuillier, Louis
collection1.description:
Group portrait of five members of 1st Field Company Engineers with a French soldier (front row, centre). Identified in this photograph is 204 Sapper Patrick Finn Walshe. Originally from Tralee in Ireland, Walshe was working as a plumber in Paddington, New South Wales when he enlisted. He died of wounds on 5 March 1917, and is buried at the Dernancourt Communal Cemetery Extension. Note that the Australian soldiers wear sheepskin vests, gloves and mittens to ward off the cold in what was one of the coldest winters in decades on the Somme.

collection1.name: P10550.261
collection1.type: Black & white - Glass original postcard negative
collection1.author: Thuillier, Louis
collection1.description:
Portrait of 2673 Driver James Stokes (left), 12th Field Company Engineers; and his brother 2253 Private (later Sergeant (Sgt)) Charles Albert Stokes DCM, 51st Battalion. Sgt Charles Albert Stokes was awarded the Digstinguished Conduct Medal in May 1918 for conspicuous gallantry and devotion to duty. While leading a section of bombers against some machine gun positions, all the section, except for himself, became casualties. He then, single-handedly, attacked one of the remaining machine guns and captured it. He took command of his platoon upon returning, his commanding officer having been wounded.
Both from Perth, WA, the two brothers met up in Vignacourt when their units were both stationed there in January 1917, and had this photograph taken. Both brothers returned home to Australia in 1919.

collection1.name: P10550.276
collection1.type: Black & white - Glass original postcard negative
collection1.author: Thuillier, Louis
collection1.description:
Group portrait of signallers from the 5th Battalion. From left to right: 3981 Private (Pte) William Pinkerton; 3980 Lance Corporal Horace Arnold Parton; 3976 Lance Corporal Ernest Gladstone Cubbins. Pinkerton, a grocer from Prahran, Victoria, and Cubbins, a salesman from Kew, Victoria were both awarded the Military Medal for their bravery while repairing communication lines during the Third Battle of Ypres in September 1917. Pte Pinkerton sustained a shrapnel wound to his right knee in August 1918, and after convalescing returned to Australia in May 1919. Horace Parton was an accountant from Richmond, Victoria, and with Cubbins and other members of their unit sustained injuries from gas in August 1918. Both also returned to Australia in May 1919. (See also P10550.689).
Horace Parton enlisted in the Second World War and served as a Warrant Officer with RAAF Headquarters in Melbourne. He was hospitalized with illness possibly relating to the gas injuries from his earlier service, and he died in December 1943 at the age of 52.

collection1.name: P10550.305
collection1.type: Black & white - Glass original postcard negative
collection1.author: Thuillier, Louis
collection1.description:
Studio portrait of (probably) 2960 Private (Pte) Alexander Henry McLaren, Port Fairy, Vic; and 877 Pte Edwin Carlill Morrison, Gippsland, Vic, both of the 29th Battalion. Pte McLaren, a carpenter prior to enlistment on 26 January 1916, embarked from Melbourne aboard HMAT Euripides (A14) in April that same year. He was killed in action at Morlancourt on 30 July 1918. Pte Morrison, a contractor, embarked from Melbourne aboard HMAT Ascanius (A11) on 10 November 1915, and was killed in action on 26 September 1917. He was one of three brothers who enlisted from a family of fifteen children. His brother, 2728 Pte Walter Beatson Morrison, 22nd Battalion, was also killed in action in May the same year. Pte Morrison's sister, Annie, later married Pte McLaren's brother, John.
From the Thuillier collection of glass plate negatives. Taken by Louis and Antoinette Thuillier in Vignacourt, France during the period 1916 to 1918.

collection1.author: Thuillier, Louis

2374 Pte George Gordon Gilbert, a labourer from Birmingham, England, was killed in action on 22 August 1918. (See also P10550.121)

collection1.name: P10550.396
collection1.type: Black & white - Glass original postcard negative
collection1.author: Thuillier, Louis
collection1.description:
Group portrait of four Australian soldiers of the 12th Field Company Engineers. Identified, standing right, is 5439 Sapper Charles Edward Haworth. A wheelwright from North Carlton, Victoria, Haworth enlisted in September 1915 and embarked with the 5th Field Company Engineers. He was transferred to the 12th Field Company Engineers in May 1916. Sapper Haworth's unit was based at Vignacourt for several weeks in the winter of 1916-17 while undertaking a number of different engineering projects in the surrounding area. He returned to Australia in May 1919. (See also P10550.226 and P10550.396)
From the Thuillier collection of glass plate negatives. Taken by Louis and Antoinette Thuillier in Vignacourt, France during the period 1916 to 1918.

collection1.name: P10550.614
collection1.type: Black & white - Glass original postcard negative
collection1.author: Thuillier, Louis
collection1.description:
Portrait of Lieutenant (Lt) Herbert Crowther Foxton (left) and 2nd Lt Cecil Arthur Auchterlonie MC and bar (right), 25th Battalion. Lt (later Captain) Foxton, a watchmaker from Ireland, enlisted in Toowoomba, Queensland. He was gassed in October 1917 and suffered serious shrapnel wounds to his face in July 1918. He was sent to hospital in England where he underwent a series of operations to reconstruct his face (see AWM photos P06131.001 - .012). Captain Foxton returned to Australia in 1921.
2nd Lt (later Lt) Auchterlonie, a clerk from Gympie, Queensland, was awarded the Military Cross for actions near Villers Brettoneux in July 1918. Later that month he was awarded a bar to his Military Cross. He was killed in action on 10 August 1918.

collection1.name: P10550.679
collection1.type: Black & white - Glass original postcard negative
collection1.author: Thuillier, Louis
collection1.description:
Portrait of two Australian soldiers. Identified, left, is 2904 Sergeant (Sgt) Angus Valentine Wilson, 4th Pioneer Battalion, a milkman from Williamstown, Victoria. Originally embarked with the 14th Battalion, Angus Wilson was transferred to the 4th Pioneer Battalion in March 1916. Sgt Wilson was awarded the Military Medal for courage and determination while leading a platoon on the night of 4 July, 1918. His platoon marked out a communication trench between the front line and support trenches under heavy enemy fire, and the recommendation for the Military Medal stated that Sgt Wilson 'showed great determination, courage and resource throughout.' (See also P10550.173)
From the Thuillier collection of glass plate negatives. Taken by Louis and Antoinette Thuillier in Vignacourt, France during the period 1916 to 1918.

collection1.type: Black & white - Glass original postcard negative
collection1.author: Thuillier, Louis
collection1.description:
Group portrait of members of the 18th Battalion. Identified are: Front row, left to right: 5691 Private (Pte) Vincent William Kelly, 6370 Pte Donald Cameron Monroo McLeod, 6369 Pte George Angus McLeod, 2425 Pte George McIntyre MM. Back row: unidentified, unidentified, 6286 Pte John Patrick Carroll, unidentified, 6369 Pte Henry William Saunders, 6074 Pte Maurice Gelle. (See also P10550.044 and P10550.146)
2425 Pte George McIntyre was awarded the Military Medal for his actions on 3 October 1918 near Joncourt when he showed gallantry and devotion to duty by traversing open ground, continually under machine gun fire, to obtain communications with the commanding officers of two other companies.
